<div class="content_well top">
	<div class="the_hub_content_wrapper the_hub_article">
		<div class="the_hub_content">
		<a href="/category/the-hub/" class="header_link">
		<div class="the_hub_title_wrapper">
			<div class="the_hub_logo">
				<img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/plugins/lb-content-widgets/img/lit-horn.svg">
			</div>
			<div class="the_hub_title">
				<h1>The Hub</h1>
			</div>
			<div class="the_hub_slogan">
				<h1>News, Notes, Talk</h1>
			</div>
		</div>
		</a>
		
				<div class="the_hub_item">
			<div class="banner_img">
				<a href="https://lithub.com/so-you-want-to-read-some-horror/" title="So, you want to read some horror? Here&#8217;s a spooky season starter kit for the genre-curious.">
		    		<img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ghostreader.jpg" alt="" class="post_ft entry_post"/>
		    	</a>
			</div>
			
			<div class="post_content">
				<h1 data-report-url="/so-you-want-to-read-some-horror/"><a href="https://lithub.com/so-you-want-to-read-some-horror/">So, you want to read some horror? Here&#8217;s a spooky season starter kit for the genre-curious.</a></h1>
				
				<div class="author_info">
					<div class="author_photo"><img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/image-1000x10001-1-e1686319696288-100x100.png" width="100" height="100" alt="Drew Broussard" class="avatar avatar-100 wp-user-avatar wp-user-avatar-100 alignnone photo" /></div>
					<div class="author_name">By&nbsp;<a href="https://lithub.com/author/drewbroussard/" itemprop="url"><span itemprop="name">Drew&nbsp;Broussard</span></a></div>
					<div class="author_hr"><hr/></div>
					<div class="publish_date">October 1, 2024, 2:16pm</div>
				</div>
				
				<p>Ah, October: some might say it&#8217;s the best month of the year. (It is.) Certainly, it is the spookiest (although Charles Dickens might argue for December) and by the time you read this, I have no doubt that your neighborhood will already be inundated with skeletons, pumpkins, misc. spice blends, colorful leaves, and so forth. I myself spend the month of October reading spooky (or spooky-adjacent) books—a ritual that began after college that has come to be one of my favorite reading traditions, and one I&#8217;m always keen to pass along to others. There&#8217;s nothing like seasonally-appropriate reading at any time of the year, but a good chiller can be just the thing for this most autumnal of months.</p>
<p>But what about you, dear reader? I&#8217;m imagining that you&#8217;ve maybe never picked up a horror novel, or that you&#8217;ve been curious but always a little unsure of where to begin. Maybe you&#8217;ll even continue: &#8220;But, Drew, your enthusiasm for the season is infectious. Perhaps this year I&#8217;ll give it a shot!&#8221;</p>
<p>Well, friend: you&#8217;ve come to the right place. I&#8217;ve curated for you a short list of books with which to begin. Welcome to the October Country.</p>
<p>NB that for this list I have purposefully avoided anything written pre-1950. If you are so inclined, by all means check out Edgar Allan Poe or H.P. Lovecraft (or, actually, skip Lovecraft as his frights are reliably diminished by his racism and bad prose) or <em>Frankenstein </em>or <em>Dracula</em> or Matthew Lewis&#8217;s <em>The Monk</em> or Jane Austen&#8217;s <em>Northanger Abbey&#8230; </em>my intention here is to introduce you to the modern field, as it were.</p>
<h2 style="text-align: center;"><strong>If you&#8217;re looking for a gentle introduction to horror&#8230;</strong></h2>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="243714" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/so-you-want-to-read-some-horror/bradbury-4/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bradbury.jpg" data-orig-size="390,595" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="bradbury" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bradbury-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bradbury.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-243714" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bradbury-197x300.jpg" alt="" width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bradbury-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bradbury-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bradbury-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bradbury.jpg 390w" sizes="(max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Ray Bradbury, <a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9781501167713" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Something Wicked This Way Comes</em></a></strong></p>
<p>Bradbury is the patron saint of the October Country—indeed, one of his most beloved story collections gave me that name. Plenty of his best-known work exists in the science-fiction realm but <em>Something Wicked This Way Comes</em> is the closest Bradbury ever came to writing a straight-up horror novel, albeit one still tinged with his trademark nostalgia. Mr. Dark and his mysterious carnival are frightening enough to keep the pages turning but likely won&#8217;t give you nightmares, and the book&#8217;s warm heart is a perfect reminder that spooky season also means comfy sweaters and warm fires.</p>
<p><strong>Fear-o-Meter: 3</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="243713" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/so-you-want-to-read-some-horror/weenies/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/weenies.jpg" data-orig-size="330,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="weenies" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/weenies-220x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/weenies.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-243713" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/weenies-220x300.jpg" alt="" width="220" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/weenies-220x300.jpg 220w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/weenies-44x60.jpg 44w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/weenies-37x50.jpg 37w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/weenies.jpg 330w" sizes="(max-width: 220px) 100vw, 220px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Emily Hughes, <a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9781683694250" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Horror for Weenies</em></a></strong></p>
<p>Not fiction and not really about books—but I know that reading the Wikipedia synopses of scary books/movies has provided an entrée into the genre for a great many readers out there and there&#8217;s nothing wrong with that! Hughes&#8217;s book, which looks at 25 classic horror movies from the 1960s to the present, is like a more-personable version of those synopses: she walks you through films like <em>Psycho</em> and <em>The Blair Witch Project</em> while explaining why they&#8217;re important, why their take on horror is meaningful, and how any particular vein of horror (psychological, slasher, folk, zombie, cosmic, etc) has manifested over the years. If you&#8217;re horror-curious, this could be a place to safely check out what you like and what you&#8217;d rather avoid—and it&#8217;ll give you some Halloween-party-ready thoughts on classic films to boot.</p>
<p><strong>Fear-o-Meter: 2</strong></p>
<h2 style="text-align: center;"><strong>If you want to start with the best of the best&#8230;</strong></h2>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="243712" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/so-you-want-to-read-some-horror/the-shining-3/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/the-shining.jpg" data-orig-size="794,1199" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;HA.com&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="the shining" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/the-shining-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/the-shining-678x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-243712" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/the-shining-199x300.jpg" alt="" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/the-shining-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/the-shining-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/the-shining-768x1160.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/the-shining-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/the-shining-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/the-shining.jpg 794w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Stephen King, <a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9780307743657" class="external" target="_blank"><em>The Shining</em></a></strong></p>
<p>You could put just about any of Stephen King&#8217;s first ten books on this list and the list wouldn&#8217;t be complete without him—but for my money, <em>The Shining </em>is the place to start. It was my first of King&#8217;s horror novels, and while I think a few others are ultimately scarier, it is still the one that lingers in the shadowy corners of my mind. It has, along with a lot of King&#8217;s work, begun to show its age (fair warning: horror has been an unfortunate repository for a lot of misogyny and racism over the years) but there&#8217;s a reason that this book and its spiritually-faithful-but-literally-unfaithful film adaptation have landed so firmly in popular consciousness. Also, King&#8217;s book is far better than the Kubrick film. It&#8217;s more human, more humane, and a lot more interesting—not to mention scarier: this one will definitely going to keep you up at night.</p>
<p><strong>Fear-o-Meter: 8</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="243715" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/so-you-want-to-read-some-horror/rice/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/rice.jpg" data-orig-size="912,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="rice" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/rice-182x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/rice-623x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-243715" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/rice-182x300.jpg" alt="" width="182" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/rice-182x300.jpg 182w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/rice-623x1024.jpg 623w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/rice-768x1263.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/rice-36x60.jpg 36w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/rice-30x50.jpg 30w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/rice.jpg 912w" sizes="(max-width: 182px) 100vw, 182px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Anne Rice, <a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9780345337665" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Interview With The Vampire</em></a></strong></p>
<p>Maybe you&#8217;re watching the surprisingly-great series on AMC, maybe you remember the pretty-good film, maybe you&#8217;re just a goth kid at heart who also wants love—maybe you&#8217;re even just a romance reader who wonders if you might be able to jump from <em>The Ex Hex</em> to something a little more pulse-pounding (in every way). Let me assure you: Anne Rice&#8217;s vampires will both frighten and seduce you. <em>Interview</em> is not the best book in the series (for my money, that&#8217;s <em>Queen of the Damned</em>) and the series loses its way several times over the decades (CW: religion and lots of it) but when Rice really gets cooking, nobody can top her. There&#8217;s plenty of bloodsucking violence but also a ton of homoerotic passion: Rice doesn&#8217;t get as spicy in these books as she did in her erotica, but not by much. This book and its first few sequels helped humanize horror for me, showing that fear and arousal (and laughter!) all live quite close to one another in the body.</p>
<p><strong>Fear-o-Meter: 6</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="243716" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/so-you-want-to-read-some-horror/hill-house-2/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/hill-house.jpg" data-orig-size="298,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="hill house" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/hill-house-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/hill-house.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-243716" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/hill-house-199x300.jpg" alt="" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/hill-house-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/hill-house-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/hill-house-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/hill-house.jpg 298w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Shirley Jackson, <a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9780143122357" class="external" target="_blank"><em>The Haunting of Hill House</em></a></strong></p>
<p>Don&#8217;t let the Netflix series confuse you: Jackson&#8217;s best-known novel is neither an unabashed fright-fest nor a saccharine and overly-monologue-y family drama. It is, however, one of the scariest books ever written because of how well it depicts an unreliable narrator&#8217;s experience of the uncanny. It&#8217;s possible to read this book as a haunting/possession novel and it is also possible to read it as a portrait of a troubled mind—and the truth lies, likely, somewhere in the middle. There are no bent-backed wraiths here to provoke a jump scare—but true terror, as you&#8217;ll learn, comes from the wondering, from the possibility of something just around the corner, from the sudden shocking realization that you might not be able to trust your own senses&#8230;</p>
<p><strong>Fear-o-Meter: 5</strong></p>
<h2 style="text-align: center;"><strong>If you&#8217;re short on time (or attention span)&#8230;</strong></h2>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="243718" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/so-you-want-to-read-some-horror/mr-gaunt/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mr-gaunt.jpg" data-orig-size="526,800" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="mr gaunt" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mr-gaunt-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mr-gaunt.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-243718" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mr-gaunt-197x300.jpg" alt="" width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mr-gaunt-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mr-gaunt-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mr-gaunt-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mr-gaunt.jpg 526w" sizes="(max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>John Langan, <a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9781956252002" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Mr. Gaunt and Other Uneasy Encounters</em></a></strong></p>
<p>Any of John Langan&#8217;s collections could work for the eager but commitment-wary reader, but I&#8217;ll offer up his first as a great place to start. Langan is one of the best writers working in the horror field today, committed to delivering great scares but also thoughtful meditations on the human condition—which, I should warn you, is one of the most potent undercurrents in the genre across time. This collection has a bunch of classic setups—an expedition to a remote island, a mysterious bequest, a journey across a post-apocalyptic wasteland, an impossible statue, skeletons—but it blends those classic ideas (and the energy of classic horror or horror-adjacent writers like Henry James and Washington Irving) with a deeply readable modern verve. One or two Langan stories is enough to hook you for life.</p>
<p><strong>Fear-o-Meter: 6</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="243717" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/so-you-want-to-read-some-horror/come-closer/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/come-closer.jpg" data-orig-size="1000,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="come closer" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/come-closer-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/come-closer-683x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-243717" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/come-closer-200x300.jpg" alt="" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/come-closer-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/come-closer-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/come-closer-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/come-closer-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/come-closer-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/come-closer.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Sara Gran, <a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9781641295246" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Come Closer</em></a></strong></p>
<p>I&#8217;ve <a href="https://tornightfire.com/tales-from-the-backlist-sara-grans-come-closer-is-waiting-for-you/" class="external" target="_blank">written about this book before</a>, but I&#8217;ll never pass up an opportunity to say that it is one of the scariest books I&#8217;ve ever read. It&#8217;s also a short, sharp shock of a read: you can polish it off in a day or two, tops. Indeed, you&#8217;ll likely <em>want</em> to finish it in the hopes of getting it out of your head. It is, at its heart, a possession story and a pretty obvious one: Gran doesn&#8217;t pull any punches or obfuscate much of what is happening to her main character as she embraces and descends into a dark partnership. But where the horror really kicks in is the &#8220;am I possessed&#8221; quiz that pops up early in the book—I won&#8217;t spoil it except to say that Gran ensures the terror slips off the page and into your real world so smoothly you almost won&#8217;t notice. Until, of course, you do.</p>
<p><strong>Fear-o-Meter: 9</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="243719" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/so-you-want-to-read-some-horror/imago/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/imago.jpg" data-orig-size="1012,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="imago" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/imago-202x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/imago-691x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-243719" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/imago-202x300.jpg" alt="" width="202" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/imago-202x300.jpg 202w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/imago-691x1024.jpg 691w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/imago-768x1138.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/imago-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/imago-34x50.jpg 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/imago.jpg 1012w" sizes="(max-width: 202px) 100vw, 202px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Laird Barron, <a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9781597801461" class="external" target="_blank"><em>The Imago Sequence</em></a></strong></p>
<p>Another contemporary writer, Laird Barron works largely in the &#8216;cosmic&#8217; horror realm—a kind of horror inspired by the works of H.P. Lovecraft and Arthur Machen and Robert Chambers, which looks at unknowable entities from other dimensions or from across the cosmos whose sheer existence so warps the state of reality that it will leave any human who encounters them permanently scarred. Barron&#8217;s stories often have a bit of noir to them as well (he&#8217;s since added crime novelist to his resume) and the blend of tough guys facing down mind-bending horrors provides a refreshing spin on both. His stories can often be mind-bending in their scope, but that&#8217;s part of the fun.</p>
<p><strong>Fear-o-Meter: 7</strong></p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="243720" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/so-you-want-to-read-some-horror/sunny-shady/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/sunny-shady.jpg" data-orig-size="1000,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="sunny shady" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/sunny-shady-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/sunny-shady-683x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-243720" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/sunny-shady-200x300.jpg" alt="" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/sunny-shady-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/sunny-shady-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/sunny-shady-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/sunny-shady-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/sunny-shady-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/sunny-shady.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Mariana Enriquez (tr. Megan McDowell), <a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593733257" class="external" target="_blank"><em>A Sunny Place for Shady People</em></a></strong></p>
<p>Enriquez is another author who can be read from any point in her oeuvre—her novel <em>Our Shade of Night</em> was my hands-down favorite of 2023—but her latest short story collection is a perfect encapsulation of not only her particular brand of the uncanny but a terrific introduction to the vibrant Latin American horror scene. Even the title is fitting: shady people but in sunny places? Hmm, seems&#8230; unsettling, doesn&#8217;t it? Many of her stories deal with violence towards women, the hauntings that linger inside of relationships (familial, romantic, or even friendly), and the strange corners of the world that resist illumination. Of this whole list, she&#8217;s probably the most &#8216;literary&#8217; pick—but make no mistake, she&#8217;ll also make you wonder about the things going bump in the night beyond your door.</p>
<p><strong>Fear-o-Meter: 3</strong></p>
<h2 style="text-align: center;"><strong>If you want something of-the-moment&#8230;</strong></h2>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="243723" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/so-you-want-to-read-some-horror/image-625x1000/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/image-625x1000-1.png" data-orig-size="625,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="image-625&#215;1000" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/image-625x1000-1-188x300.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/image-625x1000-1.png" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-243723" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/image-625x1000-1-188x300.png" alt="" width="188" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/image-625x1000-1-188x300.png 188w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/image-625x1000-1-38x60.png 38w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/image-625x1000-1-31x50.png 31w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/image-625x1000-1.png 625w" sizes="(max-width: 188px) 100vw, 188px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Michael Bettendorf, <a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9781959790235" class="external" target="_blank"><em>TRVE CVLT</em></a></strong></p>
<p>Some of the best horror writing happening today is coming out of small and/or genre-specific presses like Tenebrous Press, Bad Hand Books, Word Horde, and of course Tor Nightfire. This choose-your-own-adventure styled &#8220;gamebook&#8221; is full of everything great in horror today: playful experimentation with form, genuinely frightening scares, a re-examination of recent societal fears like the Satanic Panic and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backmasking" class="external" target="_blank">backmasking</a> and toxic masculinity, and a beating human heart at the core of it all. Plus, did I mention it has a choose-your-own-adventure structure? Come play with us!</p>
<p><strong>Fear-o-Meter: 7<br />
</strong></p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="243721" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/so-you-want-to-read-some-horror/ring-shout/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout.jpg" data-orig-size="926,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="ring shout" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout-185x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout-632x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-243721" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout-185x300.jpg" alt="" width="185" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout-185x300.jpg 185w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout-632x1024.jpg 632w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout-768x1244.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout-37x60.jpg 37w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout-31x50.jpg 31w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/ring-shout.jpg 926w" sizes="(max-width: 185px) 100vw, 185px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>P. Djèlí Clark, <a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250767028" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Ring Shout</em></a></strong></p>
<p>Remember earlier when I said that you can skip Lovecraft because of the racism? Several Black authors have sought to address the inherent racism in Lovecraft&#8217;s work and the work he inspired—Clark&#8217;s barn-burner of a novella goes even further, directly linking the KKK and <em>Birth of a Nation</em> with unknowable cosmic entities bent on destruction. It remains unfortunately timely, as Republicans ramp up overtly racist attacks on people of color in this country. Read it before the election and it&#8217;ll help light a fire under you, to remember that that evil must be fought at every turn in order to protect not only ourselves but our fellow human beings.</p>
<p><strong>Fear-o-Meter: 7</strong></p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="243722" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/so-you-want-to-read-some-horror/bury-your-gays/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bury-your-gays.jpg" data-orig-size="1650,2550" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="bury your gays" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bury-your-gays-194x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bury-your-gays-663x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-243722" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bury-your-gays-194x300.jpg" alt="" width="194" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bury-your-gays-194x300.jpg 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bury-your-gays-663x1024.jpg 663w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bury-your-gays-768x1187.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bury-your-gays-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bury-your-gays-994x1536.jpg 994w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bury-your-gays-1325x2048.jpg 1325w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bury-your-gays-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/bury-your-gays.jpg 1650w" sizes="(max-width: 194px) 100vw, 194px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Chuck Tingle, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250874658" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Bury Your Gays</em></a></strong></p>
<p>I&#8217;ve already mentioned this book in several of our <a href="https://lithub.com/18-new-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/">most-anticipated/books-you-should-read</a> roundups and those shout-outs should serve as a primer for the read, but I&#8217;ll add this: Chuck is one of the recent wave of writers whose work is consciously moving horror in a more inclusive direction. He&#8217;s also a wonderfully accessible writer—you don&#8217;t need to know or like horror to necessarily enjoy this book, which does traffic in some classic Hollywood-horror-related tropes but you&#8217;ll know those if you&#8217;ve watched a TV procedural or a Marvel movie in the last twenty years. What&#8217;s more, this&#8217;ll remind you (or teach you!) that horror might be scary but it can also be empowering.</p>
<p><strong>Fear-o-Meter: 4<br />
</strong></p>
